{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012YDgqJfFsB565thMTgWwHn","type":"tool_result","content":"# Marketing Surface Pattern Groups\n\nBased on the document, the **10 confirmed pattern groups** are: `marketing`, `application-ui`, `commerce`, `docs`, `data-display`, `forms`, `navigation`, `overlays`, `feedback`, `layout`.\n\nFor marketing surfaces specifically, **`marketing`** is the primary pattern group. The document states:\n\n> \"site-blueprint's sitemap(9종)·homepage sections(7종) is this 10종's **partial exposure**\"\n\nThis indicates that marketing surfaces use a subset of the 10 pattern groups, with `marketing` being the foundational category.\n\nHowever, **the document does not explicitly detail which pattern groups serve \"about\" pages, story/intro sections, or location/contact/directions sections.** Those content-specific applications would fall under `marketing` pattern group but require consulting the referenced `surface-taxonomy.md` for detailed guidance on \"lower types, typical elements, and agent cues.\"\n\nThe document establishes this as the \"single source of truth\" for taxonomy, with surface-specific implementation details delegated to other referenced documents rather than detailed here."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f1423542-66b2-49e0-a02f-d7685d2196fd","uuid":"ae9eea9c-4f51-4df0-b767-afa4fb298c83","timestamp":"2026-07-18T14:51:43.910Z","tool_use_result":{"bytes":5273,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Marketing Surface Pattern Groups\n\nBased on the document, the **10 confirmed pattern groups** are: `marketing`, `application-ui`, `commerce`, `docs`, `data-display`, `forms`, `navigation`, `overlays`, `feedback`, `layout`.\n\nFor marketing surfaces specifically, **`marketing`** is the primary pattern group. The document states:\n\n> \"site-blueprint's sitemap(9종)·homepage sections(7종) is this 10종's **partial exposure**\"\n\nThis indicates that marketing surfaces use a subset of the 10 pattern groups, with `marketing` being the foundational category.\n\nHowever, **the document does not explicitly detail which pattern groups serve \"about\" pages, story/intro sections, or location/contact/directions sections.** Those content-specific applications would fall under `marketing` pattern group but require consulting the referenced `surface-taxonomy.md` for detailed guidance on \"lower types, typical elements, and agent cues.\"\n\nThe document establishes this as the \"single source of truth\" for taxonomy, with surface-specific implementation details delegated to other referenced documents rather than detailed here.","durationMs":4521,"url":"https://ui.askewly.com/llms/docs/design-system/pattern-taxonomy.md"}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011hzbZWAB139FxWCEHvKd9K","type":"tool_result","content":"# Anti-Patterns to Avoid for Marketing/About Pages\n\nBased on the guide, here are the key anti-patterns applicable to marketing and landing pages:\n\n## 1. **Concept Dashboard Inertia**\nAvoid loading hero sections with \"Good morning\" messages, decorative photography, or charts without axes. Marketing pages should prioritize user value over aesthetic flourish. Empty design elements undermine credibility.\n\n## 2. **Flattened Hierarchical Content**\nDon't collapse nested information (team structure, product tiers, feature categories) into flat lists. Preserve relational clarity—\"'cautions' should remain grouped, not scattered across separate cards\" maintains information architecture integrity.\n\n## 3. **Design Token Bypass**\nResist hardcoding visual effects like oversized radii or heavy shadows \"because they look common.\" \"Verify that radius/shadow/gradient values exist in DESIGN.md before applying them\" prevents brand drift.\n\n## 4. **Color-Only Status Signaling**\nNever rely on color alone for meaning (success/urgency/promotion status). Text labels must accompany visual cues to ensure accessibility for colorblind users and screen readers.\n\n## 5. **Typography Multiplication**\nAvoid adding new typefaces for hierarchy. Manage variation through weight, size, and color within one or two core typefaces—additional fonts create visual confusion rather than clarity.\n\n## 6. **Pure Ink/Paper Values**\nUse softened blacks (95% alpha) and warm-tinted bases instead of #000/#fff to avoid a cheap, harsh appearance typical of AI-generated content.\n\n---\n\n**For marketing pages specifically**: Prioritize genuine user benefit over decorative concepts. Clarity and hierarchy matter more than ornament."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f1423542-66b2-49e0-a02f-d7685d2196fd","uuid":"2127dae3-11c6-444f-92e8-006790013eb3","timestamp":"2026-07-18T14:51:46.341Z","tool_use_result":{"bytes":21544,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Anti-Patterns to Avoid for Marketing/About Pages\n\nBased on the guide, here are the key anti-patterns applicable to marketing and landing pages:\n\n## 1. **Concept Dashboard Inertia**\nAvoid loading hero sections with \"Good morning\" messages, decorative photography, or charts without axes. Marketing pages should prioritize user value over aesthetic flourish. Empty design elements undermine credibility.\n\n## 2. **Flattened Hierarchical Content**\nDon't collapse nested information (team structure, product tiers, feature categories) into flat lists. Preserve relational clarity—\"'cautions' should remain grouped, not scattered across separate cards\" maintains information architecture integrity.\n\n## 3. **Design Token Bypass**\nResist hardcoding visual effects like oversized radii or heavy shadows \"because they look common.\" \"Verify that radius/shadow/gradient values exist in DESIGN.md before applying them\" prevents brand drift.\n\n## 4. **Color-Only Status Signaling**\nNever rely on color alone for meaning (success/urgency/promotion status). Text labels must accompany visual cues to ensure accessibility for colorblind users and screen readers.\n\n## 5. **Typography Multiplication**\nAvoid adding new typefaces for hierarchy. Manage variation through weight, size, and color within one or two core typefaces—additional fonts create visual confusion rather than clarity.\n\n## 6. **Pure Ink/Paper Values**\nUse softened blacks (95% alpha) and warm-tinted bases instead of #000/#fff to avoid a cheap, harsh appearance typical of AI-generated content.\n\n---\n\n**For marketing pages specifically**: Prioritize genuine user benefit over decorative concepts. Clarity and hierarchy matter more than ornament.","durationMs":6224,"url":"https://ui.askewly.com/llms/docs/design-system/anti-patterns.md"}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FR3Y6zYkNwXRa8cTJVfC5E","type":"tool_result","content":"# Askewly Design Principles: Summary\n\n## Core Approach\n\nAskewly design starts with **user task and hierarchy**, not decoration. The system prioritizes restraint, semantic clarity, and complete interaction over visual polish.\n\n## Key Principles\n\n**1. Task-First Composition**\nBegin by naming the user's job and primary surface. Establish content hierarchy and dominant action before visual treatment. As the document states: *\"A large hero, card grid, or dashboard shell is not a substitute for the real working surface.\"*\n\n**2. Hierarchy Through Restraint**\nReserve accent treatment for one focal action per viewport. Secondary elements recede through outline, spacing, and placement rather than competing fills. The aim is organized clarity, not uniform emphasis.\n\n**3. Meaningful Motion**\nMotion should clarify state change or sequence, not decorate. *\"The interface must remain coherent when animation is paused or reduced, and every loop needs a valid resting state.\"* Perpetual activity without purpose reads as decoration.\n\n**4. Semantic Tokens Over Literals**\nAll color, type, and spacing reference the design system's intent-based tokens. Generated files derive from a single source of truth—`tokens/askewly.tokens.json`—preventing ad hoc values from leaking into product code.\n\n**5. Complete Interaction**\nKeyboard navigation, focus behavior, empty states, errors, and responsive fallback are mandatory, not optional. A component lives only when its edge cases work.\n\n**6. Specific Evidence, Not Generic Proxies**\nExamples prove reusable capabilities with realistic content, data, and domain structure—never fake dashboards or decorative blobs.\n\n**7. Publish Only Finished Work**\nUnfinished content stays behind development gates. Public surfaces promise real assets and working interaction."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f1423542-66b2-49e0-a02f-d7685d2196fd","uuid":"992c1a9a-b302-4c17-ac73-d0b7809046f5","timestamp":"2026-07-18T14:51:47.501Z","tool_use_result":{"bytes":7821,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Askewly Design Principles: Summary\n\n## Core Approach\n\nAskewly design starts with **user task and hierarchy**, not decoration. The system prioritizes restraint, semantic clarity, and complete interaction over visual polish.\n\n## Key Principles\n\n**1. Task-First Composition**\nBegin by naming the user's job and primary surface. Establish content hierarchy and dominant action before visual treatment. As the document states: *\"A large hero, card grid, or dashboard shell is not a substitute for the real working surface.\"*\n\n**2. Hierarchy Through Restraint**\nReserve accent treatment for one focal action per viewport. Secondary elements recede through outline, spacing, and placement rather than competing fills. The aim is organized clarity, not uniform emphasis.\n\n**3. Meaningful Motion**\nMotion should clarify state change or sequence, not decorate. *\"The interface must remain coherent when animation is paused or reduced, and every loop needs a valid resting state.\"* Perpetual activity without purpose reads as decoration.\n\n**4. Semantic Tokens Over Literals**\nAll color, type, and spacing reference the design system's intent-based tokens. Generated files derive from a single source of truth—`tokens/askewly.tokens.json`—preventing ad hoc values from leaking into product code.\n\n**5. Complete Interaction**\nKeyboard navigation, focus behavior, empty states, errors, and responsive fallback are mandatory, not optional. A component lives only when its edge cases work.\n\n**6. Specific Evidence, Not Generic Proxies**\nExamples prove reusable capabilities with realistic content, data, and domain structure—never fake dashboards or decorative blobs.\n\n**7. Publish Only Finished Work**\nUnfinished content stays behind development gates. Public surfaces promise real assets and working interaction.","durationMs":6654,"url":"https://ui.askewly.com/llms/docs/design-system/principles.md"}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016NVdzB2gqJ22hTTxJze2Vx","type":"tool_result","content":"# Askewly Style Signature: Core Criteria\n\n## 5 Operating Principles\n\n1. **Token Derivation** — \"모든 색·치수는 프로젝트 토큰에서 파생한다\" (all color and dimension values originate from project tokens, never invented literals)\n\n2. **Accent as Signal** — Emphasis colors serve functional signaling (primary actions, selection states, status) in small areas only, not as surface coverage\n\n3. **Restrained Hierarchy** — One focal point per viewport; layering built through spacing, typography, borders, and surface changes rather than competing emphasis\n\n4. **Complete States** — All applicable states (hover, focus, active, disabled, empty, error) exist and function in both light and dark modes\n\n5. **Experimental Touch is Manual** — Intentional asymmetry, overlaps, and decorative experiments are not agent-initiated; they require human finalization or explicit request\n\n## 5 Hard-Fail Dislikes\n\n1. **Left Color Line Cards** — \"카드 좌측면에 세로 액센트 라인을 붙이는\" (vertical accent borders on card left edges)\n\n2. **Korean Text Mid-Word Break** — Hangul text split across lines due to missing `word-break: keep-all`\n\n3. **Awkward Line Breaks** — Headlines breaking without semantic consideration; requires `text-wrap: balance` or manual review\n\n4. **Emoji Icons** — UI elements using emoji instead of inline SVG icons\n\n5. **Rough CSS** — Misaligned elements, unexplained magic numbers, unstyled interactive elements, exposed browser defaults, or inline values ignoring tokens"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f1423542-66b2-49e0-a02f-d7685d2196fd","uuid":"ea1fbf50-7c61-41cd-b408-c1089ee18daa","timestamp":"2026-07-18T14:51:47.953Z","tool_use_result":{"bytes":4325,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Askewly Style Signature: Core Criteria\n\n## 5 Operating Principles\n\n1. **Token Derivation** — \"모든 색·치수는 프로젝트 토큰에서 파생한다\" (all color and dimension values originate from project tokens, never invented literals)\n\n2. **Accent as Signal** — Emphasis colors serve functional signaling (primary actions, selection states, status) in small areas only, not as surface coverage\n\n3. **Restrained Hierarchy** — One focal point per viewport; layering built through spacing, typography, borders, and surface changes rather than competing emphasis\n\n4. **Complete States** — All applicable states (hover, focus, active, disabled, empty, error) exist and function in both light and dark modes\n\n5. **Experimental Touch is Manual** — Intentional asymmetry, overlaps, and decorative experiments are not agent-initiated; they require human finalization or explicit request\n\n## 5 Hard-Fail Dislikes\n\n1. **Left Color Line Cards** — \"카드 좌측면에 세로 액센트 라인을 붙이는\" (vertical accent borders on card left edges)\n\n2. **Korean Text Mid-Word Break** — Hangul text split across lines due to missing `word-break: keep-all`\n\n3. **Awkward Line Breaks** — Headlines breaking without semantic consideration; requires `text-wrap: balance` or manual review\n\n4. **Emoji Icons** — UI elements using emoji instead of inline SVG icons\n\n5. **Rough CSS** — Misaligned elements, unexplained magic numbers, unstyled interactive elements, exposed browser defaults, or inline values ignoring tokens","durationMs":6523,"url":"https://ui.askewly.com/llms/docs/design-system/style-signature.md"}}
